    <chapter xml:id="chap-proof-techniques">
      <title>Proof Techniques</title>
      
      <section xml:id="sec-direct-proof">
        <title>Direct Proof</title>
        
        <assemblage>
          <title>Guiding Questions</title>
          <p>
              <statement>
              In this section, we'll seek to answer the questions:
              <ul>
                <li>What is a proof?</li>
                <li>What is a direct proof?</li>
                <li>What are some ideas for getting started/unstuck when stuck on a proof?</li>
              </ul>
        
            </statement>
          </p>
        </assemblage>
        
        <introduction>
          <p>
            Unlike the natural and social sciences, which largely rely on data, experiment, and statistical analyses, mathematical knowledge proceeds deductively via proof.
            But what is a proof?
            We will consider a proof to be a <q>convincing argument,</q> written as a short essay, and adhering to the standard rules of mathematical English.
            But what is an argument? And whom should it convince?
          </p>
          <p>
            As an illustration, consider a statement of the form <q>If <m>P</m>, then <m>Q</m>.</q>
            A <term>direct proof</term> will begin with the assumption that statement <m>P</m> is true.
            We will use our knowledge of what it means for <m>P</m> to be true<mdash />using other definitions or theorems<mdash />to make a new deduction.
            We continue in this way until we may deduce that <m>Q</m> is true.
          </p>
        </introduction>
        
        <p>
          Before an example, we make the following definition.
        </p>
        
        <definition xml:id="def-even-odd-integer">
          <idx>even integer</idx>
          <idx>odd integer</idx>
          <idx><h>integer</h><h>even</h></idx>
          <idx><h>integer</h><h>odd</h></idx>
          <statement>
            <p>
              Let <m>m</m> be an integer.
            </p>
            <ul>
              <li>We say that <m>m</m> is <term>even</term> if there exists an integer <m>k</m> such that <m>m = 2k</m>.</li>
              <li>We say that <m>m</m> is <term>odd</term> if there exists an integer <m>\ell</m> such that <m>m = 2\ell + 1</m>.</li>
            </ul>
          </statement>
        </definition>
        
        <activity>
          <statement>
            <p>
              Determine whether the following integers are even or odd by showing that they satisfy the appropriate definition.
            </p>
            <ol>
              <li>5</li>
              <li>8</li>
              <li>0</li>
              <li>1</li>
              <li><m>-57</m></li>
              <li>8,675,309</li>
            </ol>
          </statement>
        </activity>
        
        <p>
          We now consider the following example proof.
          For the purposes of this proof and what follows, we may assume that the basic laws of arithemtic of integers are true: an integer times an integer is an integer, an integer plus an integer is an integer, etc.
        </p>
        
        <theorem xml:id="thm-sq-even">
          <statement>
            <p>
              Let <m>m</m> be an even integer.
              Then <m>m^2</m> is even.
            </p>
          </statement>
          <proof>
            <p>
              Let <m>m</m> be an even integer.
              By <xref ref="def-even-odd-integer" />, there exists an integer <m>k</m> such that <m>m = 2k</m>.
              When we square <m>m</m>, we obtain <m>m^2 = (2k)^2 = 2^2 \cdot k^2 = 4k^2</m>.
              Observe that we may rewrite <m>m^2</m> as
            </p>
              <me>
                m^2 = 4k^2 = 2(2k^2).
              </me>
            <p>
              Since <m>2k^2</m> is an integer, we have written <m>m^2</m> as the product of 2 and an integer.
              Therefore, <m>m^2</m> is even.
            </p>
          </proof>
        </theorem>
        
        <insight>
          <index><h><m>\LaTeX</m> symbols</h><h>exponents</h></index>
          <statement>
            <p>
              To typeset an exponent in <m>\LaTeX</m>, we use the carat symbol, <c>^</c>, in math mode.
              So, <c>m^2</c> produces <m>m^2</m>.
              If the exponent has more than one character, enclose the expression in the exponent in curly braces; so, <c>m^{n+2}</c> produces <m>m^{n+2}</m>.
            </p>
          </statement>
        </insight>
        
        <p>
          There are several observations that are worth a moment of our time.
        </p>
        
        <assemblage>
          <title>Observations on the Proof of <xref ref="thm-sq-even" /></title>
          <p>
              <statement>
              
              <ul>
                <li>The proof begins by restating our assumtion: that we are working with a general even integer, <m>m</m>.</li>
                <li>Note that we are <em>not</em> considering a specific even integer, such as 18, and verifying that its square is even. Part of the power of mathematics is that we have tools for proving <em>general</em> statements about all even integers at once. Proofs are not examples, and you shouldn't treat them as such.</li>
                <li>The proof is written using complete sentences!</li>
                <li>The proof takes the reader on a journey, using plural pronouns and active language: <q>we may rewrite...,</q> etc.</li>
                <li>The proof avoids the use of pronouns to refer to a mathematical objects; we don't square <q>it</q>, we square <m>m</m>. This keeps things clear and easy to follow.</li>
                <li>Each step follows from the one before it, though specific reasons are not always cited. Determining when it's appropriate to cite, say, a definition or theorem by number is a bit of an art form. We'll figure it out.</li>
                <li>The proof ends by clearly stating the conclusion we sought.</li>
                <li>You should consider your audience. If your audience is a group of research mathematicians, you'll write a far different proof than if you are writing for your classmates. You should write for your classmates.</li>
              </ul>
        
            </statement>
          </p>
        </assemblage>
        
        <p>
          Prove the following theorems directly.
        </p>
        
        <theorem>
          <statement>
            <p>
              Let <m>n</m> be an odd integer. Then <m>n^2</m> is an odd integer.
            </p>
          </statement>
        </theorem>
        
        <theorem>
          <statement>
            <p>
              The sum of two even integers is even.
            </p>
          </statement>
          <hint>
            <p>You should give your integers (distinct) names.</p>
          </hint>
        </theorem>
        
        <p>
          For the next three theorems, finish the sentence with <q>even</q> or <q>odd,</q> then prove the theorem.
        </p>
        
        <theorem>
          <statement>
            <p>
              The sum of two even integers is ....
            </p>
          </statement>
        </theorem>
        
        
        <theorem>
          <statement>
            <p>
              The sum of two odd integers is ....
            </p>
          </statement>
        </theorem>
        
        
        <theorem>
          <statement>
            <p>
              The sum of an even integer and an odd integer is ....
            </p>
          </statement>
        </theorem>
        
        
        <p>
          An <term>axiom</term> is an unproved assumption.
          Without axioms, we have no starting point for our explorations and deductions.
          However, since we do not prove our axioms, we should ensure that they are reasonable and clear.
          We will likely eventually prove <xref ref="axiom-evenodd" />, but for now we may take it as true without proof.
        </p>
        
        <axiom xml:id="axiom-evenodd">
          <statement>
            <p>
              Let <m>m</m> be an integer.
              Then <m>m</m> is even or odd, but not both.
            </p>
          </statement>
        </axiom>
        
        <p>
          First, a definition.
        </p>
        
        <definition xml:id="def-consecutiveintegers">
          <idx><h>integer</h><h>consecutive integers</h></idx>
          <idx>consecutive integers</idx>
          <statement>
            <p>
              Let <m>m,n</m> be integers.
              We say <m>m</m> and <m>n</m> are consecutive integers if <m>m = n+1</m> or <m>n = m+1</m>.
            </p>
          </statement>
        </definition>
        
        <p>
          Again, in the next two theorems, finish the statement with <q>even</q> or <q>odd</q>, and prove the theorem.
        </p>
        
        <theorem>
          <statement>
            <p>
              The product of consecutive integers is ....
            </p>
          </statement>
        </theorem>
        
        
        <theorem>
          <statement>
            <p>
              Let <m>m</m> be an integer.
              Then <m>m^2 + 13m + 42</m> is ....
            </p>
          </statement>
        </theorem>
        
        <question>
          <statement>
            <p>
              Of the theorems so far in this section, which are universally quantified?
              Which are existentially quantified?
              Justify your answer.
            </p>
          </statement>
        </question>
        
        <subsection>
          <title>Exploring Graphs</title>
          
          <p>
            Let's prove some facts about graphs.
          </p>
          
          <definition xml:id="def-vertex-degree">
            <idx>degree of a vertex</idx>
            <statement>
              <p>
                Let <m>v</m> be a vertex in a graph <m>G</m>.
                The <term>degree of <m>v</m></term>, denoted <m>d(v)</m>, is the number of edges incident to <m>v</m>.
                We say a vertex is <term>even</term> if its degree is an even integer, and <term>odd</term> if its degree is an odd integer.
              </p>
            </statement>
          </definition>
          
          
          
          <activity>
            <statement>
              <p>
                Draw at least three examples of graphs.
                For each graph you draw, count the following:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>The number of odd vertices.</li>
                <li>The number of even vertices.</li>
                <li>The sum of all the vertex degrees.</li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                Make a careful conjecture (that is, an educated guess) about any patterns you observe.
                Then prove your conjectures.
              </p>
            </statement>
          </activity>
          
          <definition xml:id="def-min-max-degree">
            <statement>
              <p>
                Let <m>G</m> be a graph.
                The <term>minimum degree</term> of a vertex in <m>G</m> is denoted by <m>\delta(G)</m>.
                The <term>maximum degree</term> of a vertex in <m>G</m> is denoted by <m>\Delta(G)</m>.
              </p>
            </statement>
          </definition>
          
          <insight>
            <index><h><m>\LaTeX</m> symbols</h><h><m>\delta</m></h></index>
            <index><h><m>\LaTeX</m> symbols</h><h><m>\Delta</m></h></index>
            <statement>
              <p>
                We typeset <m>\delta(G)</m> in math mode using <c>\delta(G)</c>.
                Similarly, we typeset <m>\Delta(G)</m> in math mode using <c>\Delta(G)</c>.
              </p>
            </statement>
          </insight>
          
          <exploration>
            <statement>
              <p>
                Let <m>G</m> be a graph with <m>n</m> vertices.
                Determine, with proof, the possible values for <m>\delta(G)</m> and <m>\Delta(G)</m>.
              </p>
            </statement>
          </exploration>
          
          <exploration>
            <statement>
              <p>
                Suppose you know that a graph <m>G</m> has seven vertices, and <m>\delta(G) = 3</m> and <m>\Delta(G) = 5</m>.
              </p>
              <ol>
                <li>Prove that this graph must have at least 12 edges.</li>
                <li>Determine, with proof, the largest number of edges possible in this graph.</li>
              </ol>
            </statement>
          </exploration>
        
        </subsection>
        
        
         
      
